NAME
    tail - output the last part of files

SYNOPSIS
    tail [OPTION]... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
    Print the last 10 lines of each FILE to standard output. With more
    than one FILE, precede each block with a header giving the file name.
    With no FILE, or when FILE is '-', read standard input.

    The +N form of -n and -c specifies an offset from the start of the
    file rather than from the end.

OPTIONS
    -c N, --bytes=N
        Output the last N bytes. If N begins with '+', output bytes
        starting from the Nth byte of each file.

    -f, --follow[=HOW]
        Output appended data as the file grows. HOW is 'descriptor'
        (default) or 'name' (re-open the file if truncated or renamed).
        Polls the file and outputs new lines as they appear.

    -F  Same as --follow=name --retry. Retries opening the file if it
        becomes inaccessible.

    -n N, --lines=N
        Output the last N lines (default: 10). If N begins with '+',
        output lines starting from the Nth line.

    --pid=PID
        With -f, terminate after process PID dies.

    -q, --quiet, --silent
        Never print file name headers.

    -s SEC, --sleep-interval=SEC
        With -f, sleep SEC seconds between polls (default: 1.0).

    -v, --verbose
        Always print file name headers.

    -z, --zero-terminated
        Line delimiter is NUL, not newline.

    --version
        Output version information and exit.

    --help
        Display help and exit.

EXAMPLES
    tail file.txt
        Print last 10 lines of file.txt.

    tail -n 20 file.txt
        Print last 20 lines.

    tail -f /var/log/app.log
        Follow a log file, printing new lines as they appear.

    tail -c 512 file.bin
        Print last 512 bytes.

    tail -n +5 file.txt
        Print all lines starting from line 5.

    tail -f -n 0 app.log
        Follow a log file showing only newly appended lines.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success.
    1   Error occurred.
